external_knowledge:
- 'in progress' refers to user stories that are actively being worked on;
- 'started after January 15, 2023' refers to sprints whose start dates are later than this date;
- 'at least one comment' means the user stories have received comments from users or team members.

- 'blossomed' refers to tasks that have been marked as 'done';
- 'still growing' refers to user stories that have a status of 'in progress';
- 'John Doe' is the user name of the person assigned to the user stories.

- 'to do' status indicates tasks that have not yet been started or completed;
- 'estimated_hours' represents the anticipated time required to complete each user story;
- 'Sprint 2' is a specific release or sprint in the project management context.

- A user story is a high-level definition of a requirement, containing just enough information so that the developers can produce a reasonable estimate of the effort to implement it.;
- Tasks are specific work items that need to be completed as part of a user story.;
- Comments are notes or discussions related to a user story, often used for communication among team members.

- 'High priority' user stories are those with a priority level of 'high';
- 'Developers' are users with the role 'developer';
- The average actual hours are calculated for each user story, and only those with an average greater than 2 hours are considered.

sql:
SELECT status, COUNT(user_story_id) AS count
FROM user_stories
GROUP BY status;

SELECT title, priority
FROM user_stories
ORDER BY priority DESC;

external_knowledge:
- 'Tales' refer to user stories in a project management context;
- 'Storytellers' refer to users who are assigned to these user stories;
- 'Epic saga' refers to a larger project or collection of user stories, known as an epic;
- The status of the user stories can include various states such as 'active', 'inactive', or 'suspended'.

- 'In progress' for a release means the release is actively being worked on;
- 'To do' and 'in progress' for a user story indicate the stages of the user story in the development process;
- 'High priority' indicates the importance level of the user story;
- 'Epic' is a larger container for user stories, and 'epic_id = 0' means the user story is not part of any epic.

- 'blossomed to completion' refers to tasks that are marked as completed in the system;
- 'reached its end' refers to user stories that have a status of 'done';
- 'come to a successful close' refers to sprints and releases that have a status of 'completed'.

- "storytellers" refers to users who have made comments;
- "tales" refers to comments made on user stories;
- "garden of the second sprint" refers to the 'Second sprint of the project' release.

- 'High-priority' refers to user stories that are critical and need immediate attention;
- 'To-do' status indicates that the user story or task has not been started or is pending;
- 'Developer' is a role within the project team responsible for implementing user stories.

sql:
SELECT 
    (CAST(SUM(CASE WHEN status = 'done' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS REAL) / COUNT(user_story_id)) * 100 AS user_story_completion_rate
FROM user_stories;

SELECT COUNT(*) AS top_level_stories
FROM user_stories
WHERE epic_id IS NULL;

external_knowledge:
- 'Key contributors' refers to users who have spent the most actual hours on user stories;
- 'Garden of 'Sprint 2'' refers to the projects or tasks within the 'Sprint 2' release;
- 'Hours of sunlight' refers to the actual hours spent by users on their assigned user stories;
- The results are ordered by the total actual hours spent in descending order.

sql:
SELECT r.release_id
FROM releases r
JOIN user_stories us ON r.release_id = us.release_id
WHERE us.estimated_hours = (
    SELECT MAX(estimated_hours) FROM user_stories
);

